<HL>
   REVIEW &amp; OUTLOOK (Editorial) -- Asides:
   Justice Who?
</HL>
<DATE>
07/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A14
</SO>
<IN>
LAW AND LEGAL AFFAIRS (LAW)
</IN>
<GV>
SUPREME COURT (SUP)
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   The obvious thing about Supreme Court nominee David Souter
is that few people outside of New Hampshire know much about
him, though then-Governor John Sununu appointed him to the
state Supreme Court. He's been a federal judge for less than
a year and has written very few federal opinions or
law-review articles.
   The point is that his paper trail is scant indeed, making
it tough for Senate liberals to Bork him. We're confident
that as Judge Souter's state-court opinions go on public
display, they'll demonstrate his credentials, and his
original-intent jurisprudence. Yet the Bork lynching
continues to extract its toll; something's seriously amiss
when an unknown record becomes a huge advantage in
Washington.
</LP>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
