   LEISURE &amp; ARTS:
   Time Off: Diversions and Excursions July 24-Aug. 6
</HL>
<DATE>
07/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A12
</SO>
<LP>
   ART
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   National Gallery of Art, Washington, D.C.: "George Caleb
Bingham" -- Nearly 30 paintings by the 19th-century American
genre and landscape artist, including the well-known "The
Jolly Flatboatmen" and "Fur Traders Descending the Missouri."
                                                                                                       

   Fourth Street at Constitution Avenue NW, through Sept. 30.
Chrysler Museum, Norfolk, Va.: "A Golden Age: Art and Society
in Hungary, 1896-1914" -- More than 300 works -- including
paintings, drawings, photographs, textiles, ceramics, stained
glass and furniture -- document the search for a national
style and the development of art nouveau in Hungary. Olney
Road and Mowbray Arch, through Sept. 30. The show then
travels to the San Diego Museum of Art, Nov. 10, 1990-Jan.5,
1991.
                                                                                                       

   Museum of Fine Arts, Boston: "Unlocking the Hidden Museum:
Riches From the Storeroom" -- Nearly 200 works of art from
the museum's "backstage," some of which have not been on
display for decades. Included are etchings by Rembrandt,
paintings by Millet and Fragonard, shawls from Kashmir and
Japanese netsuke. Also look for a display of fake artworks,
and a section on art conservation. 465 Huntington Ave.,
through Sept. 16.
                                                                                                       

   DANCE
                                                                                                       

   Australian Ballet: Australia's national classical troupe
tours the U.S. for the first time in 14 years with a new
generation of dancers, a new artistic director and some new
works. The dates at New York's Metropolitan Opera House
(through July 29, 212-362-6000) and at Washington's Kennedy
Center (July 31-Aug. 5, 202-467-4600) feature the U.S.
premiere of Laszlo Seregi's "Spartacus" and director Maina
Gielgud's production of "Giselle." The Costa Mesa, Calif.,
run (Orange County Performing Arts Center, Aug. 7-12,
714-556-ARTS) includes the premiere of "Catalyst," a piece by
Stephen Baynes set to Poulenc's double piano concerto.
                                                                                                       

   SPECTACLE
                                                                                                       

   "Moscow on Ice": The thaw in U.S.-Soviet relations brings
this musically eclectic company to the U.S. for the first
time. Sixty performers, many from the Moscow State Ballet on
Ice, will skate choreography inspired by sources as disparate
as Russian folk dances, classical ballet and Janet Jackson's
"Rhythm Nation." Scheduled dates on the lengthy tour include:
Atlantic City, N.J. (Convention Hall), through July 29; West
Palm Beach, Fla. (West Palm Auditorium), Sept. 7-8; Biloxi,
Miss. (Mississippi Coliseum), Sept. 9; Atlanta (Omni), Sept.
11; Miami (James L. Knight Center), Sept. 23; Reno, Nev.
(Lawlor Events Center), Sept. 26-29; Boulder, Colo.
(University of Colorado), Oct. 9-10; Oklahoma City, Okla.
(Civic Music Hall), Oct. 29-31; Seattle (Seattle Coliseum),
Nov. 20-21; Great Falls, Mont. (Four Seasons Arena), Dec.
19-20; New York City (City Center), Dec. 31, 1990-Jan. 13
1991.
                                                                                                       

   MUSIC
                                                                                                       

   New York City Opera offers a new production of Stephen
Sondheim's "A Little Night Music," in its first major New
York revival since its Tony Award-winning Broadway run in the
early '70s. The show -- to be televised on PBS Nov. 7 --
stars Sally Ann Howes as Desiree and Regina Resnik as Madame
Armfeldt. Paul Gemignani conducts. New York State Theater,
Lincoln Center, Aug. 3, 10, 12, 16, 25; and returning Oct.
16, 20, 27, Nov. 1, 4 and 7. (212) 870-5570.
                                                                                                       

   Festival of Contemporary Music at Tanglewood, Lenox,
Mass., opens with Copland's "Ceremonial Fanfare" (1969). The
program also includes works written in the past decade by
distinguished alumni from the period of Copland's tenure at
Tanglewood -- George Crumb, Jacob Druckman, Lukas Foss and
Luciano Berio. Theatre-Concert Hall, Aug. 4. Other events run
through Aug. 9. (413) 637-1600.
                                                                                                       

   New World Symphony performs four outdoor concerts as part
of Montana's Big Sky Arts Festival. Highlights include guest
appearances by Californian Wendy Chen, winner of the 1990
National Piano Competition (July 25); Free Flight, a flute,
keyboard, bass and drum quartet (July 28); and by classical
guitarist Christopher Parkening (July 30). Leif Bjaland and
John Nelson share the conducting duties. Arabesque Stage,
Meadow Village. (406) 9954211, ext. 2400.
