<HL>
   House Clears Two-Part Bill
   On SEC and Penny Stocks
</HL>
<DATE>
07/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C16
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
</IN>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE COMMISSION (SEC)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The House passed legislation that would give
the Securities and Exchange Commission enhanced enforcement
power and would attempt to curb abuses in the penny-stock
market.
   The bill, approved by voice vote, is a combination of two
pieces of legislation. One would give the SEC its first
fining power outside of insider-trading charges. In egregious
situations, it would allow the agency to bar corporate
officers and directors from serving in such capacities at
public companies.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The other piece would force penny-stock dealers to provide
additional information to investors.
   The Senate already has passed a bill similar to the
House's enforcement measure, but has no penny-stock
legislation in any advanced stage. The bills apparently were
combined to force the Senate to consider including the
penny-stock measure during a House-Senate conference on the
legislation.
   "These two bills represent a powerful expansion of the
enforcement weapons available to combat the problems of
securities fraud in general and the penny-stock market in
particular," said Rep. Edward Markey, the Massachusetts
Democrat who heads the House subcommittee on
telecommunications and finance.
   Still, the penny-stock provision represents a toned-down
version of the original bill, which the SEC had said could
curb some legitimate capital-raising activities.
</TEXT>
