   The following were among yesterday's offerings and
pricings in U.S. and non-U.S. capital markets, with terms and
syndicate manager, as compiled by Dow Jones Capital Markets
Report:
                                                                                                       

                         CORPORATES
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   NCNB Corp. -- $200 million of subordinated notes, due July
15, 2015, was priced at par to yield 10.20%. Rated single-A-3
by Moody's Investors Service Inc. and single-A-minus by
Standard &amp; Poor's Corp., the issue will be sold through
underwriters led by Merrill Lynch Capital Markets.
                                                                                                       

                          MORTGAGE
                                                                                                       

   Federal National Mortgage Association -- $500 million of
real estate mortgage investment conduit securities is being
offered in 19 classes by Kidder, Peabody &amp; Co. The offering,
Series 1990-98, is backed by Fannie Mae 9 1/2% securities.
Details on yields and prices weren't immediately available.
                                                                                                       

                        ASSET-BACKED
                                                                                                       

   Sears Receivables Financing Group -- $250 million of
pass-through securities backed by credit-card receivables
with a coupon rate of 8.70% at 99.855 to yield 8.75%. The
issue, Sears Credit Account Trust 1990C, was priced at a
yield spread of 0.41 percentage point above the Treasury's
five-year note. Maturity date is Aug. 25, 1995. Sears,
Roebuck &amp; Co. is servicing the underlying loans. The offering
is expected to be rated triple-A by S&amp;P and Moody's, based on
the quality of the underlying loans and a subordinated class
that now totals 8.5% of the senior securities. The
subordinated class absorbs losses on the senior securities.
                                                                                                       

                            OTHER
                                                                                                       

   Kingdom of Spain -- $300 million of notes, due Aug. 1,
2000, was priced at par to yield 9.125%. The noncallable
notes were priced at a spread of 0.65 percentage point above
the Treasury's 10-year note. Rated double-A-2 by Moody's and
double-A by S&amp;P, the issue will be sold through underwriters
led by Morgan Stanley &amp; Co.
                                                                                                       

                          EUROBONDS
                                                                                                       

   Nordic Investment Bank (agency) -- 30 billion yen ($201.5
million) of 7 1/4% bonds due Aug. 15, 1995, priced at par via
Nomura International Ltd.
   Landeskreditbank Baden-Wuerttemberg (West Germany) -- 300
million marks ($182.8 million) of bonds due Aug. 21, 2000,
priced at 100.10, via Trinkaus &amp; Burkhardt. Coupon for the
first two years is 9 1/2%, calculated under the German
method, or 30 days per month divided by 360. Coupon for the
final eight years is 16% less six-month Libor, based on the
Euro method, or the actual number of days per month divided
by 360.
   Credit Local de France (France) -- one billion French
francs ($181.7 million) of 10% bonds due Aug. 20, 1995,
priced at 101.72 via Societe Generale.
   General Electric Capital Corp. (U.S.) -- 150 million marks
of bonds due Aug. 21, 1997, priced at 101 1/4, via Merrill
Lynch AG. Coupon for the first two years is 9 3/4%,
calculated under the German method. Coupon for the final five
years is 15 3/4% less six-month Libor, based on the Euro
method.
   Bayerische Landesansalt fuer Aufbaufinanzierung (West
Germany) -- 100 million marks of bonds at par due Aug. 21,
1998, via Trinkaus &amp; Burkhardt. Coupon for the first two
years is 9 1/2% calculated under the German method. Coupon
for the final six years is 15 7/8% less six-month Libor,
based on the Euro method.
   General Electric Capital Corp. (U.S.) -- 125 million Swiss
francs ($89 million) of 6 3/4% public bonds due Aug. 23,
1995, priced at 101.38 via Wirtschafts &amp; Privatbank.
   Nissan Capital of America Inc. (Japanese parent) -- 10
billion yen of bonds due Nov. 16, 1993, priced at 101 1/4 via
Yamaichi International Ltd. Coupon will float 1/16 point
above the three-month yen Libor for the first three months
and thereafter will be fixed at 7 1/2%. Guaranteed by Nissan
Motor Corp. U.S.
   Skopbank (Finland) -- 10 billion yen of 7 1/2% bonds due
Aug. 16, 1993, priced at 101 3/8 via Nippon Credit
International Ltd.
