900724-0049.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Eastern Air Creditors Get
   Checchi Liquidation Plan
   ----
   A Wall Street Journal News Roundup
</HL>
<DATE>
07/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A8
</SO>
<CO>
   NWA CTA
</CO>
<IN>
AIRLINES (AIR)
BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   A proposal by Alfred A. Checchi, chairman of Northwest
Airlines parent NWA Inc., suggesting a "controlled
liquidation" of Eastern Airlines, was presented to financial
advisers for Eastern's creditors, but no action was taken.
   Under the proposal, Northwest, St. Paul, Minn., would take
over certain Eastern planes, airport gates and maintenance
facilities, and arrange the sale of the rest of Eastern's
assets to benefit its creditors, people familiar with the
proposal said. If such an arrangement materializes, Northwest
could strengthen its position on the East Coast with little
risk, while offering Eastern's creditors a resolution of the
carrier's 16-month-old proceedings under Chapter 11 of the
federal Bankruptcy Code.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Advisers to Eastern's creditors are expected to report on
the plan soon to the full creditors committee. That panel's
endorsement would probably speed the bankruptcy court
approval needed for such a proposal to take effect. Committee
representatives couldn't be reached for comment.
   Eastern reiterated it hasn't received any offer from
Northwest to acquire any part of the airline. It said that
Martin R. Shugrue Jr., the court-appointed trustee running
the airline, a unit of Houston-based Continental Airlines
Holdings Inc., has said there is no intention to liquidate
Eastern, and that the carrier is interested only in offers
for the complete operation and its employees.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900724-0048
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900724-0048.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media:
   Blackstone, Pompadur Set
   Media Investing Venture
</HL>
<DATE>
07/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B5
</SO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
</IN>
<LP>
   Blackstone Group and media investor I. Martin Pompadur
said they formed a joint venture to invest $100 million of
equity capital in domestic and foreign media and
entertainnent properties.
   The investors are entering the media market at the bottom,
which may be to their advantage as buyers. With uncertainty
in the regulatory market and the restrictions on highly
leveraged transactions that characterized the cable industry
in the past, for example, cable system sales have slowed to a
trickle. Radio and television stations have been hurt by a
difficult advertising climate, as have newspapers and
magazines.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "It's really a sluggish time" because of the various
problems confronting the industry, Mr. Pompadur said, adding
that a number of media properties could be helped with an
infusion of equity and some operating expertise. Henry
Silverman, a general partner at the Blackstone investment
firm, said his group believes it is "a perfect time to get
into the media business" because many operators are facing a
liquidity crunch. He said the venture will specifically seek
distressed situations.
   Mr. Pompadur is a longtime media executive and investor
who has raised several hundred million dollars since 1983
through various public limited partnerships for media
investments.
   Blackstone's Mr. Silverman said the $100 million will come
from Blackstone's general pool of funds.
