<DOCNO>
WSJ900724-0023
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900724-0023.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   What's News --
   World-Wide
</HL>
<DATE>
07/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   BUSH SAID he will nominate appellate judge David Souter to
the Supreme Court.
   Just three days after liberal Justice Brennan resigned for
health reasons, the president selected Souter, a former New
Hampshire Supreme Court jurist, for his first appointment to
the nation's highest court. Bush, in introducing Souter at a
White House news conference, said he hadn't asked the
50-year-old judge's opinions on such key topics dividing
liberals and conservatives as abortion and civil rights.
Souter's name is believed to have been given to Bush by his
chief of staff, former New Hampshire Gov. Sununu.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Souter, though a conservative, lacks any reputation for
the kind of conservative judicial activism that aroused such
fierce opposition to Reagan's nomination of Robert Bork in
1987.
   ---
   Aspin announced he'll join an effort to kill funding for
the B-2 bomber, representing a serious blow to Bush's effort
to build more of the radar-evading planes. The chairman of
the House Armed Services Committee, a Wisconsin Democrat,
said he will press to stop production of the B-2 bomber
beyond those that are already in development.
   ---
   The Bush administration told makers of six semiautomatic
assault-style rifles banned from import last summer that new
designs of the weapons conform to U.S. laws, according to the
Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms. A bureau spokesman
didn't know if makers had sought import permits for any of
the new weapons.
   ---
   All 79 opposition lawmakers quit South Korea's National
Assembly as the governments of South Korea and North Korea
wrangled over a plan to open their border to free travel. The
opposition politicians warned that President Roh was trying
to use relations with North Korea to divert the public from
domestic problems.
   ---
   The House passed a bill requiring broadcasters to provide
children's television programming and to limit commercial
time during children's shows. The Senate passed a similar
bill last week, but that version included a provision to
establish an endowment for creating educational shows for
children.
   ---
   Greece's parliament ratified a new defense treaty with the
U.S. that will allow two American military bases to remain on
the island of Crete for at least eight more years. The
decision ends more than 18 months of uncertainty about the
U.S. bases following the expiration of a prior treaty.
   ---
   Liberian rebel fighters waded across a swamp and shot
their way into the center of Monrovia, surprising government
troops who had been defending two bridges leading into the
capital. A U.S. official quoted President Doe as saying he
was being held hostage by his own troops.
   ---
   West German Chancellor Kohl will meet East German Prime
Minister de Maiziere on Thursday to discuss a controversy
over pan-German elections that has shaken East Germany's
coalition. De Maiziere insists that separate votes in the two
Germanys precede unification, while two coalition partners
want a single election after the union.
   ---
   The Pentagon said it was ready to begin moving U.S.
chemical weapons stored in West Germany to a remote Pacific
island where the Army is testing an incinerator for
large-scale destruction of the arms.
   ---
   The CIA denied involvement in Italian terrorism and the
assassination of Swedish Prime Minister Palme as
investigations into allegations of the agency's role got
under way in Sweden and Italy. A CIA spokesman called the
charges "absolute nonsense."
   ---
   A last-minute electrical glitch forced NASA to postpone
its launch of an unmanned Atlas rocket with a government
satellite to study the Earth's magnetic field. NASA said the
launch was delayed because the agency couldn't tell whether
the rocket had switched over to internal power.
   ---
   The U.S. and EC delayed a showdown over farm subsidies as
negotiators launched a bid to make progress at Geneva talks
aimed at a more open global economy. But Washington and
European officials said there are still policy differences,
and the U.S. said it would press for elimination of the
trade-distorting export subsidies.
   ---
   Five North African nations ended a two-day summit, vowing
to speed up economic integration. Algeria, Libya, Morocco,
Tunisia and Mauritania also called for stronger ties with the
European Community.
   ---
   More than 250,000 Bulgarians marched in Sofia to honor the
late Communist hero Dimitrov in a massive show of support for
the ruling former Communist Party.
</TEXT>
