   What's News --
   Business and Finance
</HL>
<DATE>
07/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   STOCKS PLUNGED in a broad sell-off that left the Dow
industrials down 56.44 points at 2904.70. The industrials
were off more than 105 points at one stage, triggering
"circuit breakers" that helped stanch the selling pressure.
Earnings disappointments sparked the slide, as investors
dumped growth stocks.
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   Bonds closed lower, although the rout in stocks lifted
prices sporadically throughout the day as investors sought
the safety of Treasury issues. The dollar tumbled to a
31-month low against the mark during the session.
   ---
   Loral won the bidding for Ford's aerospace unit, beating
out a Westinghouse group and GM's Hughes Aircraft and
Belgium's Alcatel.
   ---
   Merger talks were ended between Higher Education
Assistance Foundation and another student-loan guarantor,
leaving open the possibility of bank losses unless the
government agrees to a full rescue.
   ---
   RJR Nabisco posted a $108 million second-quarter loss but
strong gains in operating profit and cash flow.
   ---
   Ford Motor told dealers it plans to raise prices on most
1991 models by 4% to 5%, with some models jumping as much as
9%. Some dealers and analysts predicted Ford will have
trouble making the increases stick.
   ---
   Martha Seger may resign her post as a Federal Reserve
governor this year for personal reasons. Ms. Seger has been
the panel's most consistent advocate of easier money.
   ---
   Kansas City P&amp;L launched an $857 million tender offer for
Kansas Gas &amp; Electric in what appeared to be the first major
hostile bid in the heavily regulated electric industry.
   ---
   Time Warner incurred a second-quarter loss of $189 million
after interest payments and dividends, and cash flow rose
only 3.3% in the quarter.
   ---
   Exxon posted a big rise in second-quarter net income, but
Amoco said its profit declined 24% while Atlantic Richfield
reported a 16% drop.
   ---
   Backer Spielvogel lost one of its most prestigious clients
when Xerox pulled its $25 million-plus account and handed it
to Young &amp; Rubicam.
   ---
   Charles Schwab was fined $375,000 by the Big Board for
allegedly misusing customers' stock for its profit.
   ---
   A joint venture owned by Nestle and General Mills agreed
to buy the breakfast cereal business of Ranks Hovis McDougall
for $167 million.
   ---
   The House Judiciary Committee approved measures to
investigate the causes of the S&amp;L industry crisis and require
stiff prison sentences.
   ---
   S&amp;L bailout costs led to a budget deficit of $11.22
billion during June, a month when corporate tax payments
usually produce a surplus.
   ---
   Canadian auto workers are in a stronger position than
their U.S. counterparts as contract talks begin.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 209,030,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2904.70, off 56.44; transportation 1136.13, off 23.18;
utilities 200.20, off 1.95.
   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3429.24, off
4.27.
   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 130.69, up 0.24; spot
index 131.78, up 0.62.
   Dollar: 148.20 yen, off 0.40; 1.6220 marks, off 0.0145.
